.SH INSTALLATION (DOCKER CONTAINER)
An official debos container is available:
.IP
.EX
docker pull godebos/debos
.EE
.PP
Debos needs virtualization to be enabled on the host and shared with the
container.
.PP
Check that \f[CR]kvm\f[R] is enabled and writable by the user running
the docker container by running \f[CR]ls /dev/kvm\f[R]
.SS CONTAINER USAGE
.RS
.PP
This container should be used as an executable, i.e.\ there is no need
to add \f[CR]debos\f[R] after \f[CR]godebos/debos\f[R].
.RE
.PP
To build \f[CR]recipe.yaml\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
cd <PATH_TO_RECIPE_DIR>
docker run \-\-rm \-it \-\-device /dev/kvm \-\-user $(id \-u) \-\-workdir /recipes \-\-mount \(dqtype=bind,source=$(pwd),destination=/recipes\(dq \-\-security\-opt label=disable godebos/debos <RECIPE.yaml>
.EE
.PP
If debos fails to run the KVM fakemachine backend and the
\f[CR]/dev/kvm\f[R] device exists on your host, you may need to add the
owning group of the device as a supplementary group of the container.
This will work if \f[CR]ls \-l /dev/kvm\f[R] indicates that the owning
group has read\-write access to the device.
Adding the supplementary group may be unsafe depending on the owning
group of \f[CR]/dev/kvm\f[R], but it could be required depending on your
login provider.
To add the group, add
\f[CR]\-\-group\-add \(dq$(stat \-c \(aq%g\(aq /dev/kvm)\(dq\f[R] to
your \f[CR]docker run\f[R] command before \f[CR]godebos/debos\f[R].
See \c
.UR https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/run/#additional-groups
Docker run reference \(en Additional Groups
.UE \c
\ for more information.
.SS CONTAINER BUILD
To build the debos container image from current git branch:
.IP
.EX
docker build \-t godebos/debos .
.EE
.SH USING DEBOS IN GITHUB ACTIONS
debos can be run in GitHub Actions using the official container with KVM
support for isolated and reproducible builds.
The \f[CR]\-\-fakemachine\-backend=kvm\f[R] option is specified to
ensure KVM is used as expected:
.IP
.EX
jobs\f[B]:\f[R]
  build\f[B]:\f[R]
    runs\-on\f[B]:\f[R] ubuntu\-latest
    container\f[B]:\f[R]
      image\f[B]:\f[R] ghcr.io/go\-debos/debos:main
      options\f[B]:\f[R] \-\-device=/dev/kvm
    steps\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] uses\f[B]:\f[R] actions/checkout\(atv4
      \f[B]\-\f[R] run\f[B]:\f[R] debos \-\-fakemachine\-backend=kvm \-\-print\-recipe recipe.yaml
.EE
.SH INSTALLATION FROM SOURCE (UNDER DEBIAN)
.IP
.EX
sudo apt install golang git libglib2.0\-dev libostree\-dev qemu\-system\-x86 \(rs
     qemu\-user\-static debootstrap systemd\-container

export GOPATH=/opt/src/gocode \f[I]# or whatever suits your needs\f[R]

go install \-v github.com/go\-debos/debos/cmd/debos\(atlatest

/opt/src/gocode/bin/debos \-\-help
.EE
.SH SIMPLE EXAMPLE
The following example will create an arm64 image, install several
packages in it, change the file \f[CR]/etc/hostname\f[R] to
\f[CR]debian\f[R] and finally make a tarball of the complete system.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]{\f[R]{\- $image := or .image \(dqdebian.tgz\(dq \-\f[B]}\f[R]}

architecture\f[B]:\f[R] arm64

actions\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] debootstrap
    suite\f[B]:\f[R] trixie
    components\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] main
      \f[B]\-\f[R] non\-free\-firmware
    mirror\f[B]:\f[R] https://deb.debian.org/debian
    variant\f[B]:\f[R] minbase

  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] apt
    packages\f[B]:\f[R]
      \f[B]\-\f[R] sudo
      \f[B]\-\f[R] openssh\-server
      \f[B]\-\f[R] adduser
      \f[B]\-\f[R] systemd\-sysv
      \f[B]\-\f[R] firmware\-linux

  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] run
    chroot\f[B]:\f[R] true
    command\f[B]:\f[R] echo debian > /etc/hostname

  \f[B]\-\f[R] action\f[B]:\f[R] pack
    file\f[B]:\f[R] \f[B]{\f[R]{ $image \f[B]}\f[R]}
    compression\f[B]:\f[R] gz
.EE
.PP
To run it, create a file named \f[CR]example.yaml\f[R] and run:
.IP
.EX
debos example.yaml
.EE
.PP
The final tarball will be named \f[CR]debian.tgz\f[R].
If you would like to modify the fileame, you can provide a different
name for the variable image like this:
.IP
.EX
debos \-t image:\(dqdebian\-arm64.tgz\(dq example.yaml
.EE
